1200 Fifth Avenue
                                                                                                                                                                                                                             Columbus, Georgia
                                                                                                                                                                                                                              March 4th, 1930

Dear Mr. Anderson
Your son sent us the pictures of the house and we think its very charming.  But, of course a picture is only a flat surface and one misses the nicest of things, the color of the stones, the view, the babble of the creek. And the practical side. How many acres, rooms, do the furnish-

ings go with the house?

        I am enthusiastic over our idea of a community farm, and do hope it will work out.  First we must decide definitely what goes with the privilege of membership, how many shares we will sell, the price of them, the amount that must be collected from each member each year for taxes and upkeep. See how business like I am. I bid to be the secretary

I wish we could sell it before summer. My idea is to keep it open the three summer months, and serve meals at cost. I'd be glad to do the housekeeping, unless someone else wants the job. 
Demp and I are really anxious to drive up and see it real soon. I think I can make my descriptions much more enthusiastic if I know what I am talking about. So far I have mentioned it to only

the wife of a doctor here. She seems to think it most inviting. You'd like her. She is one of our few remaining Southern aristocrats. A beautiful creature who would grace any drawing room, and I believe any farm. We went to a wedding last night and they served champagne to hundreds of guests. A remarkable and delightful proceeding. I thought Mrs. Harres left the other day. She seemed sad, and I feel so sorry for her. It seems to me that

she would like nothing better now than permanency. Such an amazing desire! These Spring days make me too restless for words. I am the most miserable of creatures. I would like to be a Gypsy and be adored by a bold, black haired man; I owuld like to go to New York and get a job; I would like to be in Paris and be in love; I hate everybody. I wish I was on a desert island where

I never had to speak to another human being. Not that I hate everybody this particular Spring morning. I feel very expansive. I have been planting rain lilies, and I can hardly wait to dig in your Virginia garden. Write us if you have any brilliant ideas about marketing the farm. 
As ever,
Blanche Chappell

July 3rd, 1930
Dear Sherwood,
Gosh, I was glad to get your letter. Cynthia, Bemp's sister, has just had a visitor and she was just so glad when the girl went home, that it made me dubious. I wondered if you were so busy heaving sights of relief that you

would never write. Go ahead, and find out what the Anderson place will cost. You remember I told you I had enough money to build the house. .The thing is Bemp owes me $1500, and I don't want him to feel any haste about paying it. But he is perfectly solvent, he is simply too spread out on real estate holdings,

and is rather pressed at the moment for ready cash, but he has at last decided to liquidate somewhat. (He has inherited prejudice against selling anything.)
